Description: reality mode marker (suffixed to subject pronoun)
Name: *-a, -Ta

Description: alienable object (with possessive suffix), acquire an alienable object
Name: *aa-, aa-ni-
*afaŋi
Comment: _Cf._ [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _epaŋ_ glossed as ‘south’ in dictionary looks like a loan (_p_ unexpected, see [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*aúrú_ ‘south’). _Cf._ [Marck’s (1994:310/323)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*faŋi_ ‘dry season’.

Name: *afara
Comment: There appears to have been corruption of the word for ‘shoulder carrying pole’ and its reinterpretation as ‘shoulder’ in [Mortlockese](LanguageTable#cldf:mortlockese), [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese), and [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian).

Description: carry on the hip or under the arm
Name: *afi, afi-Si-
*-aki
Comment: Reflexes of this suffix that have been recorded for [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) (see examples under [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-aki-ni](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-passivesuffix-2) below) all have it followed by reflexes of _*-ni_. See the statement about [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _-ási_ (_-esi_) in [Goodenough and Sugita 1980](Sources#cldf:goodenoughandsugita1980).

Name: *alele
Comment: There is no basis for relating [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _anene_ to [Proto–Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) _*taReRe_ ‘rejoice’, as suggested by [Geraghty (1990)](Sources#cldf:geraghty1990). _Cf._ also [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) ? _*kaúlú_ ‘sing, song’ and [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*alle_ ‘count, enumerate’. There may be two different roots here.

Name: *-ali, -aliali, mʷa-aliali
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*ka-falli_ ‘be careful of, attend to’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*mʷaali_ ‘confused, mistaken’.

Name: *al[iu]ta
Comment: Note [Pulo-Annan](LanguageTable#cldf:puloannan) _d_ instead of expected _t_, there may be a problem here.

Name: *alo
Comment: [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _yaal’_ ‘sun’ is probably a loan from [Ulithian](LanguageTable#cldf:ulithian). See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*yalle-pʷuta_ ‘a tree (_Pittosporum_)’ and cf. [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*yaado_ ‘legendary woman’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*a[sS]o](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-time-1) ‘time’.

Name: *alo, aloalo, alo-[fØ]i
Comment: The [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) form appears to be a loan from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *amʷii
Comment: Could be loans in [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) and [Pingilapese](LanguageTable#cldf:pingilapese) from [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese).

Description: to have or take in hand, to handle
Name: *aŋa₁
*apara
Comment: Note that [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) seems to have reinterpreted this form as having a causative prefix and derived the secondary forms marked # accordingly. The [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) and [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) forms cannot be understood as having a causative prefix.

Name: *are, are-ki
Comment: The following forms would indicate a low stem vowel instead, as [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*ara:_.

Name: *ari
Comment: Rounding in [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) forms unexplained; possible contamination by reflexes of [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) *aru, which are now near homonyms with [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) reflexes cited here. Semantics of [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian) form help explain possible confusion between these two etyma, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*ari_ and _*aru_.

Name: *aru, aruaru, aru-ti-
Comment: Note that the initial _g_ of the [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) _garusu_ is unexpected, unless the form is a misrendering of _*(ga)-aru-su_ with a causative prefix.

Name: *atu
Comment: The _*l_ of the [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) reconstruction depends entirely on the [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) and [Saipan Carolinian·T](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancaroliniant) forms, which may result from loans.

Name: *au-
Comment: This does not seem to be cognate with [Proto–Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) _*[qØ]aRu_ ‘dew’ [Geraghty 1990](Sources#cldf:geraghty1990). See also Loans: [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _éwú-ni-yár_.

Description: 1st plural inclusive possessive pronoun, of us, our
Name: *-ca
*ca-
Comment: _Cf._ [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) _tεtε-_ or _tεtε-n_ in such honorific expressions as _tεtεmpala_, _tεtεnsik_. See [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *cafifi ‘twisted, tangled’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*ca-riwariwa_ ‘be shiny, glossy, bright, glitter’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*cééú_ ‘continuously widespread’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*cappa_ ‘be turned face down’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*coroŋo_ ‘noisy condition’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*caapaapa_ ‘flattened’.

Name: *cakai
Comment: The [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form also reflects [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*sakau_ ‘reef’, the two reflexes apparently having become homonyms closely similar in meaning, as noted by [Marck (1994:317)](Sources#cldf:marck1994), who reconstructs this as [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*t’akau_.

Name: *canu-, cacanu, canucanu
Comment: See also [Marck (1994:309)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*t’anu_ fresh water, nonsaline flowing liquids in general.

Name: *cece, cecece
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*cee, ceecee_ ‘move quickly’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*cici](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tremble-1) ‘tremble’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*rere](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tremblewithfear-1) ‘tremble (with fear)’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*caka-i-, ccaka-i-_ ‘chase, pursue’.

Name: *ceni, ceceni
Comment: Note that the vowel _e_ in the [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) form is unexpected (we expect _i_). [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _cheen_ ‘a beach heliotrope’ appears to be a loan from a Chuukic source.

Name: *ciilee
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) (?) [*cili](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-haveastyintheeye-1)‘have a sty in the eye.

Description: have a sty in the eye
Name: *cili
Comment: There seems to be a problem with the vowel of the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) (?) [*ciilee](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-swelling-1) (?) ‘swelling’.

Description: tip up, raise up, nod, bob
Name: *cimʷe
*cipʷa₂
Comment: Reference may originally have been to a green stick that was bent (broken) to make tongs. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*cipʷa₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-curvebendinward-1) ‘curve, bend inward’.

Name: *cuu, cuu-ŋi
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _su-n_ ‘to meet (someone), arrive at (a place)’ is presumably a loan.

Name: *cuyi-
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*cúyicúyi_ ‘yard, boom (of canoe)’. Note that this example, along with [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*mʷotu, mʷotu-Si](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-cutseverbreakoff-1) ‘cut, sever, break off’, shows that pre [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protooceanic) _*ns_ merged with Pre Proto-Oceanic _*nd_ and _*nt_ as [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protooceanic) _*d_, contrary to present reconstructions for [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protooceanic) ([Grace 1969](Sources#cldf:grace1969), [Ross 1988](Sources#cldf:ross1988)). For further discussion and examples, see [Goodenough 1992 fn. 6](Sources#cldf:goodenough1992), [Goodenough 1997](Sources#cldf:goodenough1997).

Description: lee platform of sailing canoe, platform on side opposite to outrigger float
Name: *epaepa
*etieti
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*[kØ]aTe-i-, [kØ]aTTe-i-_ ‘tear or peel with the teeth’.

Name: *fa-
Comment: Note [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian) _sefáŋŋ_, _sefáŋ_ and [Saipan Carolinian·T](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancaroliniant) _hefáŋ_ are metathasized forms of _fe sáŋŋ_ and *_fe háng_ respectively.

Name: *faa-
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*faa, faa-[sS]i](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-applythesoleofthefoot-1) ‘apply the sole of the foot’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*fa[ae]fa[ae]_ ‘footbrace in the form of a stationary block of wood under the warp beam of a loom’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*faa-raki_ ‘use one’s foot’.

Name: *faa-, fa-
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*faŋi](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-thenumberfourinserialcounting-1) ‘the number four’ (in serial counting).

Description: apply the sole of the foot
Name: *faa, faa-[sS]i
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*faa-](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-undersideunder-1) ‘underside, under’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*fa[ae]fa[ae]_ ‘footbrace in the form of a stationary block of wood under the warp beam of a loom’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*faa-raki_ ‘use one’s foot’.

Name: *fai, fai-a
Comment: Note that the _l_ of [Pulo-Annan](LanguageTable#cldf:puloannan) form is unexpected. [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) (_sii)-fε_ ‘devilfish, ray’ is an apparent loan.

Name: *faiSa
Comment: Note [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _e_ instead of expected _i_. See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-Saa, mee-Saa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-interrogativesuffix-1) ‘interrogative suffix’. Note also [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*fee_ ‘engage in sexual intercourse, perform an action’.

Name: *fale
Comment: Note: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _pal_ ‘house’ and [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _bare-(aka)_ ‘boathouse’ are apparent loans, in the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) case clearly from a Polynesian source.

Description: turn away, ignore the presence of others
Name: *fa-liku, fa-liku-ri-
*fanau
Comment: There may be two different roots here, or the East Chuukic languages have developed *fana- and *fféna- as analogical derivations.

Name: *faŋa
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) (_li) peŋ_ ‘give to curry favor’ is presumably a loan from a Chuukic language.

Name: *f[ao]ŋ[ou]-si-
Comment: Problems here. _Cf._ also [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *woŋ[iu]-si ‘wring out’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*ŋúTú, ŋŋúTú-, ŋúTú-ri-_ ‘to snort, blow one’s nose’.

Name: *fara
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _pér_ ‘small sprouted coconut’ is presumably a loan from [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) or [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese). _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*far[ae]](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-lungs-1) ‘lungs’.

Description: windward platform on outrigger booms next to hull of sailing canoe
Name: *farafa
*faro, faro-ki, faro-ka
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _færfær_ ‘hold, embrace’ and _færo-s_ ‘embrace or hug him or her’ appear to be loans from [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese). [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) should have rounded _r_.

Description: child of sibling of opposite sex
Name: *fa[sS]ua

Description: planted, to plant, a planted thing
Name: *faSo, fafaSo, faSo-ki, faSo-ka
*fatu
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _pæt_ ‘cornerstone’ must be construed as a loan. See also [Marck (1994:315)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*fatu_ ‘rock, stone’.

Name: *fatu, fatufatu
Comment: The _r_ in the [Pingilapese](LanguageTable#cldf:pingilapese) form _per_ ‘weave’, reported by [Bender et al. 1984](Sources#cldf:benderetal1984), is unexpected. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*fau, fau-Si](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tiebind-1)‘tie, bind’.

Name: *fatuku
Comment: Note loss of _k_ after _t_ rather than expected loss of _*t_ before _*k_ in the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form.

Name: *fau, fau-Si
Comment: Although it might appear that [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _pawpéw_ ‘bind, tie’, _pawi-t_ ‘bind something’ and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _pip_ ‘bind’, _pʷi_ ‘bind (something) could be loans from a Polynesian source such as [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _faufau_ ‘bind’, the [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) pairs _yawyéw/pawpéw_ and their transitives _yawi-t/pawi-t_ have the marks of ancient doublets, with the reduplicated pair exhibiting an _a/é_ alternation, something not found in Polynesian, but expected in [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) *_CaCu_ or *_CaCi_ reduplication, and also found in [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) ([Bender 1973](Sources#cldf:bender1973)). Other _y/p_ doublets in _Mrs_ include _yewyew_ ‘stroke, caress’, _pewpew_ ‘sweep, brush off’ and _yir_ ‘deviate’, _pir_ ‘slip down’. These doublets point to an origin as oral/nasal grade alternants (_*p/mp_) in [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protooceanic). [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _ayʌ/pip_ and _awi/pʷi_ could have this same origin ([Bender 1973:463](Sources#cldf:bender1973)). See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*fatu, fatufatu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-toweaveplait-1)‘to weave, plait’.

Description: a strip of fiber for plaiting
Name: *fica
*fici, fici-ki
Comment: There appear to be two homonymous [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) roots here bearing a relationship in meaning associations like that in English between snip (with scissors or a knife) and snap (a picture or one’s fingers). See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*pici, pici-ki](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-snapvibrate-1) ‘snap, vibrate’.

Name: *fili, filifili
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _fil-(wel)_ ‘guess, conjecture, random choice’ is a loan or unrelated.

Name: *fira, fira-[kx]i
Comment: Of these the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form can be accounted for as a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) *_fili_ ([Proto-Polynesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protopolynesian) _*firi_) ‘to braid, plait’, and the [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) forms as loans from associated [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) forms *_biri_, _biraki_. The other Micronesian forms can be accounted for as formed from the passive and transitive (with object expressed) forms of...

Name: *fiti
Comment: Note that [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _særom_ ‘light, electricity, lightning’ and [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) _jórom_ ‘lightning’ are loans from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _jarwem_ ‘electricity, lightning, electric shock, punch, hit’. See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*fiti, fiti-ki_ ‘apply fire’.

Name: *fitu, fitu-ua
Comment: Note that the _é_ instead of _ú_ in [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) _féhu-(uw)_ is unexpected.

Name: *-i-
Comment: Possible doublet of [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-ni](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-ofpertainingto-1) ‘of, pertaining to’: generic elements in [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) place names show alternation: _bekʷe-n_, _bekʷe-y_ ‘sandspit of’, _wede-n_, _wede-y_ ‘coral head of’, etc.

Description: any fish that can be caught at night
Name: *ika-ni-pʷoŋi

Description: they (independent pronoun), them (suffixed object pronoun.), their (suffixed possessive pronoun)
Name: *ira
*iri, iriiri
Comment: [Geraghty’s (1990)](Sources#cldf:geraghty1990) equation of [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _ii-a_ (his _ia_) with [Proto–Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) _*ŋkuRu_ is not supported, but see [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) ? _*fa-ia_ ‘file, rub, sharpen’. _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) ? _*faiira_ ‘to grate’.

Name: *iri, iri-pi-
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _iri-bi_ ‘to fan’, _iri-ba_ ‘to fan (something)’ is an apparent loan from a Polynesian source, e.g., [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _ili_ ‘a fan’. [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _ripóy_ ‘to fan’ is presumably a loan from [Ulithian](LanguageTable#cldf:ulithian).

Name: *isa, isa-ŋi-
Comment: [Geraghty’s (1990)](Sources#cldf:geraghty1990) deriving this from his [Proto–Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) _*Ra[cs]i_ is questionable. _Cf._ also [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) (?) *iso ‘make fire by fire plow method’.

Description: dip it up, dip it out, scoop it up
Name: *isi-fi, esi-fi
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _iti-a_ ([_isi-a_]) ‘to scoop up (water), to dip, to ladle’ is presumably a loan (we do not expect _t_ here).

Description: make fire by fire plow method
Name: *iso

Description: a float on a net, light wood
Name: *iTo

Description: causative prefix, prefix forming ordinal numerals
Name: *ka-
*kacawu
Comment: See also [Marck (1994:311)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*kat’awu_. There is a problem with the [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) forms.

Name: *kai₁
Comment: [Saipan Carolinian·T](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancaroliniant) _ahey_ ‘to husk (something) with the teeth’ is an apparent loan from [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian). See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kaŋi](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-eatsomething-1), [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) *kana.

Name: *kai₂
Comment: There is a possibility that some of these are loans.

Name: *kai-peti
Comment: The [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form makes sense as _kai_ ‘wood’ and _beti_ ‘drift’. The [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) form has reinterpreted the initial element meaning wood as a causative prefix and shortened the vowel accordingly. See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*peti, pepeti, pe(tØ)ipeti](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tofloat-1) ‘to float’.

Name: *kaka₁
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kaka₂](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tomakeanintrudingorinterruptingsound-1)‘to make an intruding or interrupting sound’.

Description: to make an intruding or interrupting sound
Name: *kaka₂

Description: roll or twist fiber into rope
Name: *kalo
Comment: There is a problem with the added final _a_ of the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form.

Name: *kalo
Comment: See also [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *kalo ‘roll or twist fiber into rope’. [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) final consonant would call for final _a_ in reconstructed form.

Description: oil for skin or hair, anoint
Name: *kapi-sa, kapi-si
*kari
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ra[wØ]u, ka-ra[wØ]u, ka-ra[wØ]u-si](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-scrapedtoscrape-1) ‘scraped, to scrape’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kara, kara-si, kara-sa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-toscrape-1) ‘to scrape’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*karu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-toscrapegrate-1) ‘to scrape, grate’, [Proto–Western Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protowesternmicronesian) *ŋani‘to, toward’.

Name: *karu
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ra[wØ]u, ka-ra[wØ]u, ka-ra[wØ]u-si](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-scrapedtoscrape-1) ‘scraped, to scrape’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kara, kara-si, kara-sa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-toscrape-1) ‘to scrape’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kari](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-toscratch-2) ‘to scratch’.

Description: white sand crab or ghost crab
Name: *karuki
*kata
Comment: [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _gaas_ ‘speak a foreign language’ appears to be a loan from a Chuukic source.

Description: lee side of a sailing canoe
Name: *katea
Comment: Note that the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form could be a loan from a Polynesian source as well as directly inherited from [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian). [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _(fa)-kata_ ‘turn a ship to port’ is an apparent loan.

Name: *kau, kakau, kau-ri, kakau-ri
Comment: There are problems with the [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) vowel.

Name: *kau, kau-ti, kau-ta
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) (?) _*kaúta_ ‘sibling-in-law of same sex, affinal relative.

Name: *kautu or *katuu
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) reflect the second reconstruction;note that the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form may be a loan because [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) lacked a local sailing tradition.

Name: *kayinaŋa
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _kaaiŋa_ ‘ancestral residence’ is a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan), as is [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _kaaina_ ‘inhabitant, occupant, citizen’.

Name: *kiaZo
Comment: For discussion of [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protooceanic) _*j_ (there _*z_), see [Goodenough (1992, fn. 8)](Sources#cldf:goodenough1992). See also [Ross (1988:79, 344)](Sources#cldf:ross1988).

Name: *kica
Comment: Note that [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _kéj_ and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _kʌt, kitε--(l)_ indicate a [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) doublet _*kita_.

Name: *kiepʷu
Comment: Note that [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _kiyopʷ_ is an apparent loan from [Mortlockese](LanguageTable#cldf:mortlockese) or _Pul_.

Name: *kima
Comment: It looks as if the [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese), [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese), and [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) forms are inherited reflexes of the [Uraustronesisch](LanguageTable#cldf:uraustronesisch), whereas the [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese), [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian), and [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) are loans from [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese).

Name: *kio, kio-ri
Comment: The _s_ of the [Ulithian](LanguageTable#cldf:ulithian) form is unexpected.

Name: *koca
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*koco₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tocut-1) ‘to cut’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kota](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-cutbreak-1) ‘cut, break’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) (?) [*koo, koo-na](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tentaclestrandofhairorfiber-1) ‘tentacle, strand of hair or fiber’.

Name: *koca, oca
Comment: It is evident that we have doublets in [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) as well as [Proto–Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protoeasternoceanic), reflecting both [Proto–Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) initial _*k_ and initial _*q_. See discussion by [Geraghty (1983:161)](Sources#cldf:geraghty1983).

Name: *kona
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kona](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-acatchasoffishtocatch-1) ‘a catch (as of fish), to catch’.

Description: a catch (as of fish), to catch
Name: *kona

Description: tentacle, strand of hair or fiber
Name: *koo, koo-na

Description: go aground, run on a reef
Name: *koso

Description: bivalve shell, shell knife or grater
Name: *koyi
*kulu
Comment: Note [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) form has unexpected expression of final vowel. _Cf._ [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) (?) _*koyikoyi_ ‘piping or whistling sound, piping bird’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*kul[iu]ŋa_ ‘plover’.

Name: *kumʷu
Comment: We cannot account for the _m_ of [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) instead of expected _mʷ_.

Description: pulled back, pull back (of foreskin or eyelid)
Name: *kura, kura-ti, kura-ta

Description: any of several kinds of fish
Name: *kuu
*laŋi
Comment: See also [Marck (1994:308)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*laŋi_. In some languages (e.g., [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian), [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian), and [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese)), ‘bad weather’ meanings are to be found primarily in derived forms. Note that [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _ḷaŋi-(n)_ has contrastive heavy _ḷ_ where light _l_ would be expected, with _i_ in next syllable, whereas heavy _ḷ_ is to be expected in the _ḷaŋe-(n)_ of a popular saying. Why the second vowel of this latter form is lowered in not understood, but it provides an explanation for the heavy _ḷ_s in the [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) ‘bad weather’ forms.

Name: *laŋua
Comment: Loss of second vowel in [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) forms is a problem. [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) rounded _ŋʷ_ expected.

Name: *lapa
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*lúkú-lapa_ ‘ocean side (of an island or reef)’ (lit. ‘great outside’).

Name: *lau
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*tokolau](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-northerlyfromthenorth-1)‘northerly, from the north’. See [Marck (1994:313)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*lau_.

Name: *l[ao]u
Comment: The [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) form could be a loan from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *laZe
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *ale ‘kind of coral’, [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *laxa ‘kind of coral’. See also [Marck (1994:313)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*laje_.

Name: *lea or *laya
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) (_te)-raa_ ‘one width of a mat sail’ is an apparent loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _laa_. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*[sS]aku-laara](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-swordfishmarlin-1) ‘swordfish, marlin’.

Name: *lee-, law-
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ni[ae]](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-place-1)‘place’. [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _in-_ has much the same distribution: place names, topographic features, body parts (but also forms personal names, as does _ni-_).

Name: *lele
Comment: [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _rerei_ ‘good, excellent’ is a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _lelei_ ‘be good’.

Description: agentive prefix indicating “one who (does, is given to doing”) (like English suffix -er)
Name: *li-
*liki, likiliki, liki-Si
Comment: This could be the same root as [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*liki, liki-Sa, liki-Si](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-discardeddiscard-1) ‘discarded, discard’.

Name: *liku
Comment: See also [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *fa-liku, fa-liku-ri- ‘turn away, ignore the presence of others’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*lúkú-lapa_ ‘ocean side (of an island or reef)’ (lit. ‘great outside’).

Name: *[ln]ima
Comment: [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _niim_ ‘bailer’ is an apparent loan from a Chuukic source.

Name: *lima, lima-ua, lim-manu, lima-ŋawulu
Comment: See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-ua](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-generalclassifierincountingsuffixedtonumerals-1) general classifier in counting (suffixed to numerals).

Name: *l[iu]nuru
Comment: The _*nn_ in [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic), _ll_ in [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese), _l_ in [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean), and _r_ in [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) and [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) suggest that [Uraustronesisch](LanguageTable#cldf:uraustronesisch) _*l_, _*n_, and _*r_ followed different patterns of assimilation in the several Micronesian languages. _Cf._ [Marck (1994:325)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*luru_.

Name: *liŋoliŋo
Comment: The _n_ in the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form indicates it is not a loan from a Polynesian source. _Cf._ [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *l[eo]ŋu ant.

Name: *lukuma
Comment: (These [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) and [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) forms probably stand in a borrowing relationship, possibly with [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese)). _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*Lukuma_ ‘bundle’ posited by [Goodenough (1995:76)](Sources#cldf:goodenough1995) and [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*sukusuku, suku-ma, suku-mi](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-bewrappedapackagetowrapsomething-1) ‘be wrapped, a package, to wrap (something)’.

Description: be furled (of a sail), rolled or folded up
Name: *lulu
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*lumi](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tofold-1) ‘to fold’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*llima_ ‘lower rim of a sail’.

Name: *lumi
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *lukuma ‘fold, wrap’:, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*llima_ ‘lower rim of a sail’.

Name: *luuka
Comment: Short first syllable of [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) needs explanation.

Description: stative prefix indicating that what is described is an appearance or condition of being
Name: *ma-
*mai₁
Comment: Note: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _mos_ does not appear to be cognate.

Name: *maki
Comment: Note the _h_ in [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) and _Ø_ in [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) where we would expect _k_. In the [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) case the _h_ suggests the word is a loan from [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese). [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian) _ile-más_, _ili-mes_, _li-más_ and [Saipan Carolinian·T](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancaroliniant) _ine-mes_ ‘love medicine’ appear to be loans from [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese).

Name: *malala
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*malle, malemale, (ka)-malemale-(a), male-di-_ ‘ground cleared of vegetation, swidden field’. And cf. [Marck (1994:322)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*mala_ and _*malala_.

Name: *maleku, maleleku, malekuleku
Comment: The reflex _n_ instead of _l_ in the [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) forms is unexpected. The [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) form reflects _*malakolako_; use of _-ló/-la_ directional with [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese), [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian), and [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) forms suggests that this is contamination of earlier _*maleku-lako_ (see [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*lako, laa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-goproceedasdirectionalaway-1) ‘go, proceed, [as directional] away’). See also [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *maluoki, maluoka ‘forget’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ma-lie](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-forget-2) ‘forget’.

Name: *malemʷu
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) substitutes _ŋʷ_ for expected _ṃʷ_, possibly in dissimilation from initial _m_ (an _ŋʷ/ṃʷ_ alternation is not uncommon);also, heavy _ḷ_ is unexpected.

Description: be efficacious, have spiritual power, efficacy, spiritual power
Name: *mana, manamana

Description: living creature of land or air
Name: *manu
Comment: Note that [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) _malúk_ ‘chicken’; [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian) _malúgh_ ‘chicken’; [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) _malúge_ ‘chicken, hen’, and [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) _malεk_ ‘chicken’ are loans, more likely from [Palauan](LanguageTable#cldf:palauan) _malk_ than from [Chamorro](LanguageTable#cldf:chamorro) _mannok_.

Name: *manu
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*manu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-livingcreatureoflandorair-1) ‘living creature of land or air’.

Name: *maraa
Comment: The East Chuukic words for ‘sail’ appear to be a locally innovated causative construction (cf. [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *yuwe ‘a sail’).

Description: nipple (lit. point of breast or nursing)
Name: *mata-ni-susu
*mati-ciki
Comment: The [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) form (instead of expected _*mááyi-chik_ ) appears to be a loan.

Name: *mati-lapa
Comment: The [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) form (instead of expected _*mááyi-nap_) could result from an old loan from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *ma-toa, ma-toatoa
Comment: Note the doublets in [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) and the lack of expected _l_ in the [Kwaio](LanguageTable#cldf:kwaio) form.

Description: a cold or cough, breathe hard
Name: *maura
*mauri
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _mauri_ ‘be in good health’ is an apparent loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _mauli_.

Name: *mawolo
Comment: _Cf._ [Marck (1994:318)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*malo_ ‘concaveness, depression, valley’ (open to question because of lack of fit of [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) forms).

Name: *mece-a
Comment: The [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) form is felt by some speakers to be a loan from English metal [Rehg and Sohl 1979:59](Sources#cldf:rehgandsohl1979). In [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean), initial _*m_ occasionally became labiovelar and is reflected by _w_ or _Ø_ — the latter especially when the following vowel develops as [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _o_.

Name: *meña
Comment: [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) _mine_ ‘exist, be at a place, live , reside, there is or are’ looks like a loan.

Name: *meña-a
Comment: The raised first vowel in the [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) and [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian) forms in contrast with the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form attest to [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*ñ_. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*meña](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-thing-1) ‘thing’.

Name: *metu
Comment: Note: the _mʷ_ of [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian) and [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) is presumably a secondary formation. Note also that [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _mʷúú, mʷúú-, mʷuu, mʷuu-_ ‘era, epoch’, [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) _mʷeey_ ‘reign, era’ could be from the same [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) root.

Description: prefix indicating having a variable, oscillating, or variegated condition
Name: *mʷa-
Comment: See [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*mʷa-ŋúnúŋúnú_  ‘whisper’, [Proto–Western Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protowesternmicronesian) *-ali, -aliali, mʷa-aliali ‘circle, circling, dizzy’, [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *mʷakusu ‘be in motion’.

Name: *mʷakusu
Comment: Note that [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _mukʷi, mukʷikʷi_ ‘move’ looks like a loan (initial _m_ unexpected).

Description: length from elbow to finger tips
Name: *mʷa-nuu
*mʷaŋau
Comment: Note that the initial _m_ of the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form is unexpected and suggests it is a loan.

Name: *mʷare
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*kamʷmʷare_ ‘carry with a shoulder pole’.

Name: *mʷata[ŋØ]ala
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _ḷ_ expected. _Cf._ also [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*taka, taka-ni_ ‘stomach, have stomach for’ and [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*daa_ ‘intestine’.

Name: *mʷ[ou]a
Comment: We have here an unusual instance in the Micronesian languages in which [Proto–Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) _*u_ after _*mʷ_ was either lowered to _o_ or _a_ (presumably because of the following _a_) or was assimilated to the preceding _mʷ_ (see also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*mʷoe](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-sleep-2) ‘sleep’).

Name: *mʷoe
Comment: Here, again, we have the assimilation of [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*o_ to a preceding _*mʷ_ in [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) (see also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*mʷ[ou]a](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-aheadgoingbefore-1) ‘ahead, going before’).

Description: feminine prefix (with personal names of women)
Name: *n[ae]i-
*namʷo
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) heavy _ṇ_ expected. _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*lama₂](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-lagoonlake-1) ‘lagoon, lake’. See also [Marck (1994:314)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*nam’o_.

Name: *-ni
Comment: Often referred to as “the construct suffix”.

Description: verb suffix indicating acquisition or ownership
Name: *-ni, -na

Description: midrib of coconut frond or leaf
Name: *noko
*nu[sS]o
Comment: The [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) form appears to be an innovation.

Name: *ñai-Sa, ŋai-Sa
Comment: These forms are not irregular but preserve one or another of the two forms of [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) and [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protooceanic), as the two [West Nakanai](LanguageTable#cldf:lakalai) forms, one for past and one for future testify.

Name: *ñamʷu
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) light _n_ expected. Note that the words for ‘mosquito net’ show problems and appear to be more recent loans, at least in some cases.

Name: *ñañau
Comment: [Jackson’s (1983:374)](Sources#cldf:jackson1983) statement that this is to be derived from [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protooceanic) _*ñamu_ with inexplicable loss of intervocalic _*m_ is open to some question. _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ñaña, ñañaña](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tasteflavor-1) ‘taste, flavor’. (See also [Jackson 1983:334](Sources#cldf:jackson1983)).

Name: *ŋace
Comment: [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) _ŋara-aki_ ‘laugh heartily’ is an apparent loan from [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese). _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ŋaco](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-palategums-1) ‘palate, gums’, [Proto–Western Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protowesternmicronesian) *ŋace ‘edge’.

Name: *-ŋa-ratu
Comment: Note the reflex here of [Uraustronesisch](LanguageTable#cldf:uraustronesisch) _*R_ in [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) as _*r_ rather than as the more common reflex _*Ø_, and in [Bugotu](LanguageTable#cldf:bugotu) as _th_ rather than as the more common reflex _l_.

Name: *ŋari, ŋari-ti
Comment: See also [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *li-ŋaŋari ‘tiny louse’; and cf. [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kari](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-toscratch-2) ‘to scratch’, [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *ma-ŋari, ma-ŋariŋari ‘rough’.

Name: *ŋere, ŋereŋere
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *ma-ŋari, ma-ŋariŋari ‘rough’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ŋari, ŋari-ti](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-nibblegnawcrunch-1) ‘nibble, gnaw, crunch’, with which there has been some  confusion.

Name: *ŋii
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*ŋúnúŋúnú, mʷa-ŋúnúŋúnú_ ‘whisper’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ŋiTi](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-chantsingbenoisylaugh-1) ‘chant, sing, be noisy, laugh’. _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*ŋiLi_ ‘buzz, hum, make sound’ posited by [Goodenough (1995:76)](Sources#cldf:goodenough1995).

Name: *ŋil[ai]
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*ŋúnúŋúnú, mʷa-ŋúnúŋúnú_ ‘whisper’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ŋiTi](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-chantsingbenoisylaugh-1) ‘chant, sing, be noisy, laugh’. _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*ŋiLi_ ‘buzz, hum, make sound’ posited by [Goodenough (1995:76)](Sources#cldf:goodenough1995).

Name: *ŋoro
Comment: This could be the same root as [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ŋoro, ŋoroŋoro, [sS]i-ŋoro](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tosnore-1) ‘to snore’.

Description: that (out of sight or in the past)
Name: *oo
*paca, pacapaca
Comment: See also [Proto–Western Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protowesternmicronesian) *paca, papaca or *capa, cacapa ‘adhere’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*paca_ ‘handle, tail (of fish)’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*pecee_ ‘leg’.

Name: *pakewa
Comment: Note that the [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) form with its unexpected _k_ could be a loan from another [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) dialect.

Name: *paŋa, paŋaki
Comment: Possibly related is [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) _paŋpaŋ_ ‘side, beside, horizontal’. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*pa-](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-side-1) ‘side’. _Cf._ [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*pala_ ‘tilted’.

Name: *patiki
Comment: There are problems with the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form.

Name: *pau, paupau
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*iri, iri-pi-](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tofan-1) ‘to fan’, and cf. [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*paLu_ ‘blow (of wind)’ posited by [Goodenough (1995:77)](Sources#cldf:goodenough1995).

Name: *pawo
Comment: Note that the [Pulo-Annan](LanguageTable#cldf:puloannan) form is unexpected here, where we would expect _*pawo_.

Name: *peka
Comment: Note that [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _fɔk, foko-(n)_ ‘feces, dung, feces of’ appears to be a loan from [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) or [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese). Note also [West Nakanai](LanguageTable#cldf:lakalai) (_la)-beka-(la)_ ‘its rear end (of flying fox)’.

Name: *pekopeko or *kopekope
Comment: Note that [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _kɔf, kɔfkɔf_ is an apparent loan from English. _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*fakafaka, fafaka_ ‘coughing, to cough’.

Name: *pici, pici-ki
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*fici, fici-ki](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-snipcutsnapflick-1) ‘snip, cut, snap, flick’, [Proto–Western Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protowesternmicronesian) *pici ‘loosened, released’.

Name: *pili
Comment: The vowel of the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form seems to pose a problem. See also [Marck (1994:318)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*pili_.

Description: come into view, begin to take shape
Name: *piŋu, pʷuŋu

Description: growth or lump under the skin, spongy core of mature coconut
Name: *piri
*pʷalu
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _kafa, kafa-i_ ‘cover, put a lid on’ are evident loans from English.

Description: taro swamp, dirt as found in taro swamp
Name: *pʷalu
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto–Western Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protowesternmicronesian) *pʷalu ‘taro swamp’ ([Jackson 1986:229 fn. 4](Sources#cldf:jackson1986), and [Marck 1994:316](Sources#cldf:marck1994)). _Cf._ also [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *pʷelu, pʷepʷelu ‘dirt, soil’.

Name: *pʷasa
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _pæt_ ‘late, delayed’, instead of expected _*fæt_, is presumably a loan from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *pʷasau
Comment: Note [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _j_ instead of expected _t_, which suggests that it is a loan, but from what source is not clear.

Name: *pʷax[ae]
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*pʷaya_ ‘swarm of fish’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*pʷere](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tosproutblossom-1) ‘to sprout, blossom’. _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*pʷera](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-goorcomethroughpass-1) ‘go or come through’.

Name: *pʷelu, pʷepʷelu
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*pʷelu_ ‘dirt, soil, dirty’ ([Jackson 1986:229, fn. 4](Sources#cldf:jackson1986), and [Marck 1994:316](Sources#cldf:marck1994)). _Cf._ also [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *pʷalu ‘taro swamp, dirt as found in taro swamp’.

Name: *pʷepʷe
Comment: The [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form may be a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan), and the [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) a loan from [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese). If so, this would be the same root as in [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*pepe, pepepe](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-toskipalongflit-1) ‘to skip along, flit’.

Name: *pʷoi, pʷoa
Comment: There are problems here, especially the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _l_.

Name: *pʷon[ao]
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*pʷono, pʷono-ti, pʷono-ta](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-beshutblockedtoshutblockclose-1) ‘be shut, blocked, to shut, block, close’.

Description: be shut, blocked, to shut, block, close
Name: *pʷono, pʷono-ti, pʷono-ta
Comment: Note that the [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) and [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) initial stops are not the expected reflexes. See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*pʷon[ao]](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-wholecomplete-1) ‘whole, complete’. _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*pʷalu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-coverlid-1) ‘cover, lid’.

Name: *pʷuasa
Comment: The [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) forms could be loans from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *pʷuli
Comment: [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) and [Pingilapese](LanguageTable#cldf:pingilapese) pʷun ‘shell’ are apparent loans from [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese).

Name: *pʷupʷu
Comment: Note that the consetllation is named for the fish.

Name: *pʷu[sS]o
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*pʷuro, pʷuropʷuro_ ‘bubble, foam’. [Marck (1994:315)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) includes the forms in [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*pʷuro, pʷuropʷuro_ ‘bubble, foam’ with these forms in his [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*p’usop’uso_ ‘foam, froth’.

Description: to sound (when blown, as a trumpet)
Name: *pʷuu
*raŋi, raŋiraŋi
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*reŋa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-turmericcolor-1) ‘turmeric color’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*caŋi_ ‘to warm oneself’. [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _raŋréŋ_ (showing vowel alternation) expected.

Description: pull out with the hands from inside something
Name: *ra[wØ]u

Description: person of or belonging to (a clan, nation, or place)
Name: *re-, ri-
*reŋa
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) (_te)-reŋa_ ‘red cloth’, _reŋareŋa_ ‘to paint (something) red’ are loans from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _lega_ ‘turmeric’. _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*aŋo](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-curcumaturmericgingeryellow-1) ‘curcuma, turmeric, ginger, yellow’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*raŋi, raŋiraŋi](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-bewarmed-1) ‘be warmed’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*yalle-pʷuta_ ‘a tree (Pittosporum)’.

Name: *ripi, ripiripi, ma-ripi
Comment: The [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) form and the [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) variants with _u_ are puzzling; if their rounding is attributed to the labial consonant, it may be of some significance that the consonant remains unvelarized.

Name: *roŋo
Comment: [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _roŋoroŋo_ ‘news’ is presumed to be a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan). See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*roŋo_ ‘special knowledge of spells’.

Name: *ru[ao]-ua
Comment: See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*rua](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-two-2) ‘two’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-ua](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-generalclassifierincountingsuffixedtonumerals-1) ‘general classifier in counting (suffixed to numerals)’.

Name: *ruku₂
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*roko_ ‘bend, curve’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ruku₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tipgounderwater-1) ‘tip, go under water’, [Proto–Western Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protowesternmicronesian) *riku or *ruki ‘gather from the ground’.

Description: become aware, wake up, be surprised
Name: *rut[iu]
*[sS]aaŋa
Comment: Note that the [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) and [Pingilapese](LanguageTable#cldf:pingilapese) forms are probably loans from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *[sS]afa, [sS]afa-ŋi-
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) (?) [*[sS]afi₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-pickplucktearoff-1) ‘pick, pluck, tear off’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*daf[ei]_ ‘be open’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*tafa, tafa-si](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tocutinpiecesslice-1) ‘to cut in pieces, slice’.

Name: *sakau
Comment: See also [Marck (1994:308)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*sakau_. Note the doublet in [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian).

Name: *[sS]aku-laara
Comment: Note assimilation of [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _n_ and [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) _l_ to following _r_. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) (?) [*lea or laya](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-asail-2)‘a sail’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*[sS]aku](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-needlefish-1) ‘needlefish’.

Name: *sapa
Comment: [Pulo-Annan](LanguageTable#cldf:puloannan) _lépakaú_ ‘be capable, able, smart’ appears to be a loan from [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese), perhaps from crewmen on D. D. O’Keefe’s trading boat that operated out of Yap in the late nineteenth century.

Name: *[st]apa, [st]apa[st]apa, [st]apa-ŋi
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *tape₁ ‘busy’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*tap[ae], tap[ae]-ki](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-liftupcarrybearinoneshands-1) ‘lift up, carry, bear in one’s hands’. It looks as if the Chuukic forms with initial _t_ have resulted from an early (possibly [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic)) borrowing from another Micronesian source.

Name: *sawu
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _tau_ ‘enough, sufficient’ has an unexpected intial _t_, and cannot be a true cognate.

Name: *[sS]in[ae]
Comment: The reconstruction by [Marck (1994:309)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) of [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _* [sz]ina_ is not supported by the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) and [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) forms cited. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) (?) [*siŋa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-sunlight-1) ‘sunlight’.

Description: slice, chunk, to cut, to slice
Name: *[sS]ipa, [sS]ipa-ki
*soa
Comment: Note: there could be a problem here.

Name: *suku
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*Tuku_ ‘pound, knock’, with which there seems to have been some semantic confusion.

Description: be wrapped, a package, to wrap (something)
Name: *sukusuku, suku-ma, suku-mi
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _sroko-m_, _sroko-mi_ ‘to wrap, envelop, wrap (something)’ appear to be loans.

Name: *sulu
Comment: We cannot account for [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _téén_, _#téénú-_ or the [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) doublet _téél_.

Name: *susu
Comment: Note that [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _thuuth_ ‘breast’ appears to be a loan from [Ulithian](LanguageTable#cldf:ulithian).

Name: *-Saa, mee-Saa
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*Safa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-whatwhatrelationship-1) ‘what? what relationship?’. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) (?) [*faiSa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-dowhatwhat-1) ‘do what, what?’, [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*pʷa-ki-da_ ‘because, why’.

Name: *Siwa-ua
Comment: See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*Siwa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-nine-1) ‘nine’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-ua](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-generalclassifierincountingsuffixedtonumerals-1) ‘general classifier in counting (suffixed to numerals)’.

Name: *tafa, tafa-si
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) (?) [*[sS]afi₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-pickplucktearoff-1) ‘pick, pluck, tear off’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*[sS]afa, [sS]afa-ŋi-](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-togatherpick-1) ‘to gather, pick’, [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*daf[ei]_ ‘be open’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*tapa, tapatapa, tapa-ki](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-becutloppedtocutsomethingoff-1) ‘be cut, lopped, to cut (something) off’.

Name: *tali-
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) heavy _ḷ_ results from assimilation to following directionals, which begin with heavy consonants.

Description: side dish of meat, fish, or sauce
Name: *talia
*tano
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*itano_ ‘deposited, put away’. See [Marck (1994:317)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*tano_ ‘soil, earth, ground’.

Description: from (something), away from (usually suffixed to verbs)
Name: *taŋi
*tapa, ka-tapa
Comment: This may be the same root as [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*tapa, tapa-[kŋ]i](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-toanswer-1) ‘to answer’.

Description: lift up, carry, bear in ones hands
Name: *tap[ae], tap[ae]-ki
*tapa, tapa-[kŋ]i
Comment: This may be the same root as [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *tapa, ka-tapa ‘speak, spoken’.

Description: be cut, lopped, to cut (something) off
Name: *tapa, tapatapa, tapa-ki
*tapaka[wØ]u
Comment: [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) _sepaawo_ (sic) ‘coconut leaf mat’ is clearly a loan from another Chuukic language, and the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form may be a loan from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *tape₁
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*tap[ae], tap[ae]-ki](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-liftupcarrybearinoneshands-1) ‘lift up, carry, bear in one’s hands’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*[st]apa, [st]apa[st]apa, [st]apa-ŋi](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tohelp-1) ‘to help’.

Name: *tapʷakea
Comment: See also [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _pʷáápʷá_ ‘turtle’ and [Saipan Carolinian·T](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancaroliniant) _pʷáápʷá_ ‘turtle’, which may well be derived from _*pʷakea_.

Name: *tara
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _tataro_ ‘to pray’ and _taro-mauri_ ‘worship’ are loans from Polynesian, e.g., [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _talo_ ‘to pray’ (obsolete).

Name: *tara, tara-[sS]i
Comment: Geraghty’s reconstruction relies heavily on the Micronesian forms, which he seems to misinterpret.

Name: *taraki
Comment: [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _tarég_ ‘to sail’ is evidently a loan from a Chuukic source.

Name: *tari
Comment: Expressed final vowel without suffixed form in [Mortlockese](LanguageTable#cldf:mortlockese), [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese), [Pingilapese](LanguageTable#cldf:pingilapese), and [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) poses problem. _Cf._ also [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) (?) *atarei ‘child’.

Name: *tau₃
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _ae_ ‘who (relative pronoun)’ appears to be a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) (_i)-ai_ ‘who (relative pronoun)’.

Description: any of several kinds of sea bass
Name: *tawia
*tawu-₁
Comment: (The saw- in certain [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) high titles is probably a Polynesian loan). See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*tau₂](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-seasonsun-1) ‘season, sun’ and [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) (?) [*tawu₂](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-clanfamily-1) ‘clan, family’. There are problems.

Name: *tawu or *co[wØ]a-
Comment: The [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) and [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) forms are incompatible and probably do not both belong in this set. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*tautu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-porcupinefish-1) ‘porcupine fish’.

Name: *telu, telu-ua
Comment: See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-ua](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-generalclassifierincountingsuffixedtonumerals-1) ‘general classifier in counting (suffixed to numerals)’.

Name: *tiku or *tuki
Comment: Note that _Ø_ is the expected reflex of _*t_ in the [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) and [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) forms. The _wúkú-_ in [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _wúkú-(par)_ and [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) _wúkú-(chcha)_, _wúkú-(pak)_ appear to be the root for ‘tail’ (see [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*iku](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tail-1) ‘tail’) rather than this one.

Name: *t[iu]pʷu
Comment: Note that [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) _dipʷ, dipʷi-(n)_ ‘exogamous matrilineal clan’ is presumably a loan.

Name: *tiro, tiro-ŋi
Comment: [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _tiro-a_ ‘to inspect, scrutinize (something)’ is a loan from a Polynesian source, e.g., [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _tilotilo_ ‘look, glance’. Note the unexpected absence of an initial consonant (_t_ or _s_) in the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form, which may be a loan from [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian).

Name: *tiSaki
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*[kØ]a[tØ]ieki_ ‘to ask’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*katia, katitia_ ‘to ask, a question’.

Name: *to[ae]
Comment: Inclusion of [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) _tóó-(shigi)_ ‘careful treatment, careful consideration’ in this series ([Bender et al. 1984](Sources#cldf:benderetal1984), [Geraghty 1990](Sources#cldf:geraghty1990)) is not justifiable. There are problems here.

Name: *toki
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) doublet (_te)-toki_ ‘chisel’ would appear to be a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _to’i_ ‘adze’, since it does not show the loss of _t_ before _k_.

Name: *toko, toko-na
Comment: Note: [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese), [Mortlockese](LanguageTable#cldf:mortlockese), and [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) _wóók, wóku-n_ ‘cane, cane of’, may be related but are not inherited forms.

Name: *tuki, tukituki
Comment: Note that _Ø_ is the expected reflex in the [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) and [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) forms.

Name: *tuna
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _teṇʷ_ ‘freshwater eel’ is an evident loan from [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) — these eels are not found in the Marshalls but are known from the Eastern Carolines.

Name: *Tiri
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _mim_ ‘urinate’ is either a loan from a Polynesian source or an inherited reflex of [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protooceanic) _*mimi_ (PPn *mimi, [Fijian](LanguageTable#cldf:fijian) _mii, mimi_).

Name: *Toka
Comment: [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _toka_ ‘be placed upon, take passage, get on’ is clearly a loan from a Polynesian source.

Description: general classifier in counting (suffixed to numerals)
Name: *-ua
*uluŋa
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ulu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-extremitytoptiphead-1) ‘extremity, top, tip, head’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*uluulu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-pillowuseapillow-1) ‘pillow, use a pillow’.

Name: *umʷa, imʷa
Comment: Note that [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _lɔm_ is a probable loan (source ?).

Description: hair, feathers, scales, remove (hair or scales)
Name: *una, unauna, una-fi
*ura
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) (_te)-ura_ is an apparent loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _ula_.

Name: *u[sS]a, u[sS]a-ni, u[sS]a-na
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*u-Ti, u-Taki](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-carry-1) ‘carry’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*wua, wuawua, wua-ti, wua-ta](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-carryconveytransport-1) ‘carry, convey, transport’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*waxa₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-aframe-1) ‘a frame’, [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*waa_ ‘carry it, convey it, transport it’.

Name: *u-Ti, u-Taki
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) (?) [*u[sS]a, u[sS]a-ni, u[sS]a-na](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-cargoload-1) ‘cargo, load’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*wua, wuawua, wua-ti, wua-ta](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-carryconveytransport-1) ‘carry, convey, transport’, [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*waa_ ‘carry it, convey it, transport it’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*waxa₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-aframe-1) ‘a frame’.

Name: *wai
Comment: One of these could be a loan from the other.

Name: *waka
Comment: There is no basis for [Geraghty’s (1990)](Sources#cldf:geraghty1990) reconstruction of [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*aka_ ‘vein, sinew’. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) (?) [*ua₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tendonvein-1) ‘tendon, vein’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*waka, wakara](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-root-1) ‘root’.

Name: *walu, walu-ua
Comment: See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-ua](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-generalclassifierincountingsuffixedtonumerals-1) ‘general classifier in counting (suffixed to numerals)’.

Description: to beat, to strike with an object
Name: *w[ao]pʷo

Description: balloon fish, puffer fish, be large
Name: *wasi, wasiwasi

Description: toward or in direction of person addressed
Name: *watu
*waxa₁
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *wa[xØ]a ‘crosspiece’, [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*waa_ ‘carry it, convey it, transport it’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*wua, wuawua, wua-ti, wua-ta](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-carryconveytransport-1) ‘carry, convey, transport’.

Name: *woca
Comment: See also [Marck (1994:314)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _ot’a_, which he sees as cognate with Proto-Central Pacific _*voda_ ‘rocks in sea’.

Name: *woŋ[iu]-si
Comment: There is no basis for [Geraghty’s (1990)](Sources#cldf:geraghty1990) Micronesian reflexes of his [Proto–Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) _*ŋkiRi_ ‘squeeze’. _Cf._ [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) (?) *f[ao]ŋ[ou]-si- ‘blow (one’s nose)’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*ŋúTú, ŋŋúTú-, ŋúTú-ri-_ ‘to snort, blow one’s nose’.

Name: *wotu
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*watu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-towardorindirectionofpersonaddressed-1) ‘toward or in direction of person addressed’.

Name: *wua, wuana
Comment: There is an apparent problem with the the initial _f_ of [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean).

Name: *wua, wuawua, wua-ti, wua-ta
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) (?) [*u[sS]a, u[sS]a-ni, u[sS]a-na](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-cargoload-1) ‘cargo, load’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*u-Ti, u-Taki](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-carry-1) ‘carry’, [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*waa_ ‘carry it, convey it, transport it’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*waxa₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-aframe-1) ‘a frame’.

Description: earth oven, bake in an oven
Name: *wumʷu, wumʷu-ni-

Description: a reef fish prized as food
Name: *wumʷu-lau
*wupʷu-₂
Comment: Note that the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form could also derive from [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) (_te)-ubwu_ ‘nose, snout’. _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) [*wupʷa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-bellyabdomentorso-1) ‘belly, abdomen, torso’.
